&#xa0;
[normal]Submission from the City Growth Commission[bold] (CD0[bold]2[bold])[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]I 
[normal]note with interest 
[normal]the Communities and Local Government Committee’s
[normal] 
[normal]inquiry into
[normal] 
[normal]f
[normal]iscal devolution to cities and city regions.  
[normal]The City Growth Commission, launched in October 2013, explore
[normal]s
[normal] similar questions. 
[normal]The Commission 
[normal]is an independent and 
[normal]authorit
[normal]ative inquiry into how best to enable our cities to respond to the fiscal and economic challenges of the future
[normal], in the context of a global trend towards growth driven by mid-tier cities
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Commission will build on the growing consensus in favour of re
[normal]balancing the economy and dev
[normal]olving more power to our cities
[normal] and
[normal] ask how we can make our cities financially and economically sustainable. It will also ask how growth in other cities can complement London’s economic success and 
[normal]look at 
[normal]the relationship between devolution, reform and growth strategies in London and in our other cities. In particular, the Commission will focus on 
[normal]local 
[normal]labour market
[normal]s, skills and investment
[normal], issue
[normal]s
[normal] of critical importance to the future of our economy. 
[normal]The ul
[normal]timate objective of the Commission is to lay the foundations for a significant shift away from the centre and towards cities, and to show the next Government, of whichever party, why this is needed and how it can be achieved. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Commission’s membership 
[normal]consists of:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
